seasonOutlook: One of the most ballyhooed free agents in baseball history despite the elbow surgery that will prevent him from pitching until 2025, Ohtani"s move to the powerhouse Dodgers lineup places him in about as fantasy-friendly a circumstance as there is for a hitter. The two-time AL MVP (2021, 2023) might well bat second between the NL"s second- (Mookie Betts) and third-place (Freddie Freeman) finishers in the MVP race, and Dodger Stadium, despite its perception as being a pitching-friendly environment, was actually baseball"s second-most HR-friendly venue over the last three seasons (a 22% boost relative to the average park). Now 29, Ohtani as a hitter alone is a more attractive (and foundational) rotisserie pick thanks to his combination of elite power and speed, than he is in points leagues. In the latter format, however, veteran players are well aware that Ohtani the two-way player is far and away -- a "Wayne Gretzky circa the 1980s" type and the game"s most-valuable asset. Tuck that away, keeper leaguers, as 2024 might well bring us his best year yet with the bat, while 2025 could bring us a 2021-23 redux.
